subSubSection.paragraph:
Cell V obtriangular, half of the length of cell IV, often divided and proliferating into a branch of variable length (
Fig. 41F
, arrow) which may support some antheridia. Insertion cell separated from the perithecium. Outer appendage once or twice branched above the basal cell, sometimes bearing solitary, lateral antheridia. Inner appendage, in young thalli, consisting of two branches bearing paired antheridia arising from the basal cell; in mature thalli replaced with long sterile appendages, similar to the outers. Basal cell of inner appendage half as long and as broad than basal cell of outer appendage. [Detailed descriptions: 
Thaxter 1908
; 
Majewski 1994b
; 
Santamaria 1998
]
